post_text:
While all of us are sad for our spring athletes who are missing their seasons, we do have a positive to share. We were able to purchase a large tent for the cross country team that will also be used during track. As Jodi Twombly states "we would have never imagined this use for the tent." We are so happy that this donation is serving a vital purpose for our community.

From Jodi Twombly: Here is a big win for Hiawatha Community Hospital. Hiawatha High School has agreed to allow HCH to use the brand new tent for our outdoor Covid-19 clinic. I'm so glad we bought this tent. Thank you booster club for your donation--we would have never imagined this use for the tentüò∑üò∑

post_text:
It was so much fun seeing our teams in action at the Gatorade Scrimmage! Thanks to all who came out to show support!

This Friday is the first home football game and the Booster Club will have the tailgate. The meal will be hot dogs and chili dogs. That's the good news. In GREAT news, if you buy a membership for the Booster Club at the game, your family eats FREE and you get one of our cool, new Red Hawk cups!!! A one year membership is $25, or you could buy a lifetime membership for just $150. Don't miss out on being part of a great organization that does so much for our students!

post_text: Congratulations ladies!!! Whoop!!!
shared_text:
Hiawatha World
January 28, 2017 at 7:21 PM ¬∑

Thunder top Hawks in HIT finale

By Adam Clay

Hiawatha never got their offense rolling in Saturday's tournament championship against Nemaha Central, as the Red Hawks fell 44-32. It was the third consecutive year the two teams have faced off in the Hiawatha Invitational Tournament, with the Thunder taking the rubber match after losing in the final seconds a year ago.

Nemaha never trailed in the contest, taking off to a 6-0 start in a low-scoring first quarter that ended 6-4. Up 15-11 at the half, the Thunder doubled their output in the third quarter, stretching their lead to 30-18 at the end of the frame.

Hiawatha found themselves down by double digits in the fourth and resorted to fouling to stop the clock, but between converting free throws and offensive rebounding, Nemaha was able to sustain their lead and close out the third-seeded Red Hawks. The Thunder's Laura Mackey scored a game high 18, while Courtney Brockhoff led Hiawatha with 12 points, including 3 three pointers. Hiawatha now sits at 6-5 and Nemaha moved to 12-1. (Photos by Josephine May/Hiawatha World)
